    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-09-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-09-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="376"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d376">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Powell</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-09-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 15, 1904</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1540.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inclose to the Department the
                    naturalization certificate of Assad Kalil Abynemer, born near Beirut, Syria. <pb
                        facs="0491" n="403" xml:id="pg_403"/> On examining him he states that he
                    lived in the United States about four years (certificate states eight years);
                    that he is a merchant; that he has had no other paper; has made no declaration
                    of becoming an American citizen; that he bought this paper from a man in New
                    York (he did not know him) who stated that as he was going to Haiti he had
                    better have such document as it would help him in business: that he did not know
                    Mickel Isaac (the witness named in certificate) and that he paid for this paper
                    $50, receiving it as he was about to leave New York in January of the present
                    year.</p>
                <p>I have returned to him the same answer as I have to the others (see No. 1537,
                    September 14, 1904).</p>
                <p>I especially call the attention of the Department to a close examination of the
                    seals that are attached to these documents.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. F. Powell.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
